  "prompt": "What is a centrifugal pump?",
  "response": "A centrifugal pump is a mechanical device used to move liquids by converting rotational kinetic energy into hydrodynamic energy. Here are its key characteristics:\n\n1. Basic operation:\n- Uses a rotating impeller to increase liquid velocity\n- Creates pressure and flow by spinning liquid outward from the center of the pump\n- Typically used to transport water, chemicals, petroleum, and other fluids\n\n2. Main components:\n- Impeller (rotating component)\n- Casing (stationary outer shell)\n- Shaft\n- Bearings\n- Seals\n\n3. Working principle:\n- Impeller rotates at high speed\n- Liquid enters at the center of the impeller\n- Centrifugal force pushes liquid to the outer edges\n- Liquid is discharged through the pump's outlet\n\n4. Common applications:\n- Water supply systems\n- Industrial processes\n- Wastewater treatment\n- Agricultural irrigation\n- HVAC systems\n- Oil and gas industry\n\n5. Advantages:\n- Simple design\n- Low maintenance\n- Relatively low cost\n- Can handle large fluid volumes\n- Suitable for many liquid types\n\nCentrifugal pumps are widely used across numerous industries due to their efficiency and versatility.",
